API Endpoints
# Development query and mutation. 
All incoming payload must be encrypted and all res data are to be decrypted. 
The following headers are present in every response.
* x-encrypted-data: The encrypted response payload 
* x-nonce: Encrypted message nonce, and 
* x-public-key: the Server Public Key:
https://civilcitizens-server.onrender.com/graphql
# for single file upload:
https://civilcitizens-server.onrender.com/uploads/single
# for multiple file upload:
https://civilcitizens-server.onrender.com/uploads/multiple
Headers
# Require for all the protected functions (mutations and queries)
Authorization: Bearer <YOUR_TOKEN_HERE>
# Require for email verification
email_verification_token: EmailVerification_ <YOUR_TOKEN_HERE>
# Require for password reset
password_reset: ResetPwd_ <YOUR_TOKEN_HERE>
# Require for verification of a new phone number
phone_auth: PhoneAuth_ <YOUR_TOKEN_HERE>
# Require for verification of a new registration. It works for both phone and email registration
phone_auth: RegAuth_ <YOUR_TOKEN_HERE>
# The incoming encrypted mutation/query payload from the client
x-client-encrypted-data: YOUR_TOKEN_HERE
# The client base64 nonce value to decrypt the encrypted incoming payload
x-client-nonce: YOUR_TOKEN_HERE
# The client base64 public key value to decrypt the encrypted incoming payload and encrypt response payload
x-client-public-key: YOUR_TOKEN_HERE

CivilCitizens API

CivilCitizens API is design to encorage transparency and people involvement in the governance process, primarily in Nigeria and across Africa.

Queries

checkEmailExist

Description

Utility query function to check if email is already in use. It returns true if not availble

Response

Returns a Boolean!

Arguments
Name Description
email - String!

Example

Query
query checkEmailExist($email: String!) {
  checkEmailExist(email: $email)
}
Variables
{"email": "xyz789"}
Response
{"data": {"checkEmailExist": false}}

limit - Int!

ID

Description

The ID scalar type represents a unique identifier, often used to refetch an object or as key for a cache. The ID type appears in a JSON response as a String; however, it is not intended to be human-readable. When expected as an input type, any string (such as "4") or integer (such as 4) input value will be accepted as an ID.

Example
"4"
